<br>
I liked the way he wrote this book because his characters seem to show a little more restraint before they jump into battle. Almost like they finally realize that they've bitten off more than even they can chew. They all start realizing how easily one or any of them could die. I just thought bringing that aspect into his writing made the characters much more real.<br>
<br>
On a side note, I loved &quot;Spine of the World&quot;. It was a nice departure from Drizzt for a while. One thing I really hope is that he developes in the future is more on Artemis Entreri and Jarlaxle. &quot;Servant of the Shard&quot; was such an awesome book. That's a gold mine of a story arc right there, imo. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://jens-smileys.netfirms.com/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.cox.net/stmyers/rodiansig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#77839D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub141.ezboard.com/beverquestpeople.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vualmortalitas>Vual Mortalitas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=#D6D4D2>Fleeting Thoughts <br>
